contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

02:05.084 --> 02:07.919
<i>DEVON: They're firing Conrad.</i>

02:07.920 --> 02:10.045
<i>KIM: Security will escort you out.</i>

02:21.625 --> 02:24.935
(MICHELLE CRYING)

02:29.800 --> 02:32.969
Screaming won't make this go any faster.

02:32.970 --> 02:34.780
(MICHELLE CRIES)

02:34.781 --> 02:36.489
Or maybe it will.

02:37.933 --> 02:40.435
(CRYING CONTINUES)

02:40.436 --> 02:42.621
(HISSING)

02:42.622 --> 02:44.080
(TWO BEEPS)

02:45.441 --> 02:47.200
(CRYING)

02:47.201 --> 02:48.943
Okay.

02:48.944 --> 02:51.154
(CRYING CONTINUES)

02:51.155 --> 02:52.254
Yeah.

02:58.162 --> 02:59.261
(SIGHS)

03:03.884 --> 03:06.227
(SIGHS)

03:07.555 --> 03:10.170
♪♪

03:10.171 --> 03:13.171
- Synced and corrected by<font color="#00BFFF"> Firefly</font> -
- <font color="#00ffff">www.addic7ed.com</font> -

03:18.849 --> 03:21.142
Good morning, everyone.

03:21.143 --> 03:23.236
I'm Dr. Garrison, your chief resident.

03:23.237 --> 03:24.854
Welcome, second-year residents.

03:24.855 --> 03:26.856
You'll be getting
interns of your own today.

03:26.857 --> 03:29.105
You will be their
mentors, their teachers.

03:29.106 --> 03:31.336
Do not hesitate to work
them like pack mules.

03:31.337 --> 03:34.247
The hospital relies
on their cheap labor.

03:34.248 --> 03:36.370
No questions. There
are only two rules...

03:36.371 --> 03:38.217
no one quits, no one dies.

03:43.090 --> 03:45.057
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

03:49.212 --> 03:50.903
Uh, Dr. Pravesh?

03:50.904 --> 03:52.946
Ezra Dreyfuss, your intern.

03:52.947 --> 03:54.447
Hey, Ezra. Welcome.

03:54.448 --> 03:56.064
- And I'm Eline.
- Oh.

03:56.065 --> 03:57.808
You didn't have to come.
Your son's in good hands.

03:57.809 --> 04:00.787
- Oh, she's not my mother.
- I am also your intern.

04:00.788 --> 04:03.197
Sorry. I-I wasn't expecting...

04:03.198 --> 04:07.034
- You thought I'd be older?
- No, no, no. I... Of course not.

04:07.035 --> 04:08.552
I-I meant...

04:09.923 --> 04:11.539
There are two of you.

04:11.540 --> 04:13.374
Eline, Ezra.

04:13.375 --> 04:15.301
I'm thrilled to welcome you to Chastain.

04:15.302 --> 04:17.015
You know, on my first day as a doctor...

04:17.016 --> 04:19.572
Before you go all William
Wallace on us, I am highly

04:19.572 --> 04:21.314
allergic to any form of nut or dairy.

04:21.315 --> 04:23.898
If I come into contact with
either, I will drop dead.

04:23.899 --> 04:25.416
Sorry. Please continue.

04:25.980 --> 04:27.739
Got it.

04:27.740 --> 04:31.242
Today will set you on the course
for the rest of your lives.

04:31.243 --> 04:33.912
So, when there are tough times,

04:33.913 --> 04:37.064
just remember why you
decided to be a doctor.

04:37.065 --> 04:38.858
Eline?

04:38.859 --> 04:40.418
You ever met an intern

04:40.419 --> 04:42.921
who watched a loved one
die of an incurable disease,

04:42.922 --> 04:45.079
quit work to become a caregiver,

04:45.080 --> 04:48.187
drew inspiration from
the medical professionals

04:48.188 --> 04:50.239
they met throughout the disease,

04:50.240 --> 04:52.457
enrolled in medical
school and became a doctor?

04:54.194 --> 04:57.338
If that person is you,
then... then, yes, I have.

04:57.339 --> 04:59.313
That person is <i> not</i> me.

04:59.314 --> 05:00.910
- (CHUCKLING): Oh.
- I was teaching math

05:00.911 --> 05:02.826
to a bunch of third-grade
terrorists, and I was deeply

05:02.827 --> 05:04.727
- inspired to get the hell out of there.
- Wow.

05:04.728 --> 05:06.160
That's hilarious. Okay, my turn.

05:06.161 --> 05:09.166
Pravesh, need you and
your children in Bay 3.

05:09.167 --> 05:11.436
Thank you.

05:11.437 --> 05:14.646
Odel. Dr. Pravesh.

05:14.647 --> 05:17.724
If it's okay with you, I'd
like to have my interns observe.

05:17.725 --> 05:20.435
(COUGHS) Of course.

05:20.436 --> 05:23.080
So, uh, I've had this
cough for a few weeks now.

05:23.081 --> 05:24.731
- Okay. Just the cough?
- Just the cough.

05:24.732 --> 05:26.599
It's called an emergency room.

05:26.600 --> 05:29.335
I know, but I'm going
to Cambodia tomorrow,

05:29.336 --> 05:30.719
so I thought I'd have it checked out,

05:30.720 --> 05:32.618
and I didn't want to end up
in some remote village clinic

05:32.619 --> 05:33.781
if it got worse.

05:33.782 --> 05:36.075
Okay. Let me take a look. Deep breath.

05:36.076 --> 05:38.359
I backpacked through
Cambodia in college.

05:38.360 --> 05:40.496
- You are gonna love it.
- Yeah?

05:40.497 --> 05:44.022
I have been to England
once with the symphony,

05:44.023 --> 05:45.347
and that's about it.

05:45.348 --> 05:48.179
- Atlanta Symphony?
- Yeah. I play cello.

05:48.180 --> 05:49.681
You ever play with Gianni Balissa?

05:49.682 --> 05:52.649
- He taught me everything I know.
- Me, too.

05:52.650 --> 05:55.601
I was honorary recipient of the
Sousa Band Award for the violin.

05:55.602 --> 05:57.263
Let me guess. You're a musical genius.

05:57.264 --> 06:00.600
Uh... yeah. Yeah. (CHUCKLES)

06:00.601 --> 06:02.605
- (FOOTSTEPS RUNNING)
- HUNDLEY: Dr. Pravesh!

06:02.606 --> 06:04.482
Scooter versus fire
hydrant, we need you.

06:04.483 --> 06:05.547
Beethoven, you're with me.

06:05.548 --> 06:06.787
Eline, I want you to finish doing

06:06.788 --> 06:08.056
a full physical exam on Odel,

06:08.057 --> 06:09.609
and report back to me when you're done.

06:09.610 --> 06:12.487
- You have got to be kidding me.
- I don't think he is.

06:12.488 --> 06:14.706
More than half of hospitals pay doctors

06:14.707 --> 06:17.709
based on relative value
units instead of set salaries.

06:17.710 --> 06:19.377
Think of it as capitalism.

06:19.378 --> 06:22.945
The more procedures, biopsies,
test diagnostic surgeries

06:22.946 --> 06:24.770
you do, the more money
you'll make; it's that simple.

06:24.771 --> 06:26.384
So, what, are we car salesmen now?

06:26.385 --> 06:29.841
Commission-based pay systems
lead to rampant overtreatment.

06:29.842 --> 06:31.638
- I've seen it myself.
- You concerned we'll all see

06:31.639 --> 06:33.623
how you really measure up, Dr. Austin?

06:33.624 --> 06:34.768
Maybe you're not as valuable

06:34.769 --> 06:36.104
to the hospital as you think you are.

06:36.105 --> 06:37.721
Well, depending on your values,

06:37.722 --> 06:39.930
you might be right, Dr. Cain.

06:39.931 --> 06:43.808
This isn't a discussion, it's
Red Rock policy from now on.

06:43.809 --> 06:46.521
You'll be paid for the
volume of work you do.

06:46.522 --> 06:48.665
And quality is irrelevant.

06:48.666 --> 06:50.001
CAIN: Nobody said that.

06:50.002 --> 06:51.352
AUSTIN: Neither of you had to.

06:54.539 --> 06:56.280
Don't worry, Dr. B.

06:56.281 --> 06:57.990
You won't be out here with
the minnows for too long.

06:57.991 --> 06:59.367
I can feel it in my heart space.

06:59.368 --> 07:02.537
Ooh, sorry. Sorry, it's for my new boss.

07:02.538 --> 07:04.028
BELL: What's the meeting about?

07:04.029 --> 07:05.855
Just boring pay stuff.

07:05.856 --> 07:08.093
Nothing like what's
arranged for you tonight.

07:08.094 --> 07:09.874
Grayson, you don't run
my schedule anymore.

07:09.875 --> 07:11.374
Well, my dad hasn't caught on yet,

07:11.375 --> 07:14.455
and he called me to tell you...
now, don't hug the messenger...

07:14.456 --> 07:17.172
but, Dr. B., you're
about to present 3B Life

07:17.173 --> 07:18.432
to the U.S. of A.

07:18.433 --> 07:22.267
So suit up and get camera-ready,
'cause you're gonna be on TV.

07:22.268 --> 07:23.516
Oh, he got the spot on <i> Montel?</i>

07:23.517 --> 07:26.060
Better. STV, baby.

07:26.061 --> 07:27.429
Shopping Television?

07:27.430 --> 07:28.964
I mean, this is incredible.
This could make our...

07:28.965 --> 07:30.811
our supplement line an industry player.

07:30.812 --> 07:33.085
It all depends on you,
though, so get that face ready

07:33.086 --> 07:35.220
for the small screen.

07:40.551 --> 07:45.413
There she is. Nurse among nurses.

07:45.414 --> 07:47.498
It's so good to see you, Finn.

07:47.499 --> 07:50.819
Oh... How's the book coming?

07:50.820 --> 07:54.060
Published. Yeah, and not
self-published, either.

07:54.061 --> 07:56.090
Real published. Smell the ink.

07:56.091 --> 07:58.259
That's amazing. Congrats.

07:58.260 --> 08:00.001
I hear you and Hawkins
live together now.

08:00.002 --> 08:02.069
Sounds like Dr. Feldman
gave you an update.

08:02.070 --> 08:04.854
- I hope he's a tidy roommate.
- Mm, getting there.

08:04.855 --> 08:06.100
(BOTH LAUGH)

08:06.101 --> 08:08.434
- Yeah.
- Wow.

08:08.435 --> 08:11.043
All the details of the life of Finn.

08:11.044 --> 08:12.376
Flip to page three.

08:13.719 --> 08:19.681
_

08:19.682 --> 08:22.635
(SIGHS) I'm pretty
sure you're responsible

08:22.636 --> 08:23.760
for beating the odds.

08:23.761 --> 08:27.338
Uh, where's Conrad? I've got
a copy for him, too, so...

08:27.339 --> 08:28.932
He's not here anymore.

08:28.933 --> 08:30.573
No, he practically lives here.

08:30.574 --> 08:32.022
Well, I'm covering for him.

08:32.023 --> 08:35.332
Which means I have your test results.

08:37.515 --> 08:40.590
I wish I had better news.

08:40.591 --> 08:42.465
I've reached my final chapter.

08:42.466 --> 08:44.573
My lung function's deteriorating,

08:44.574 --> 08:46.816
which means I'll be on
a breathing machine soon,

08:46.817 --> 08:49.175
and then will go the way of
all my friends with Duchenne.

08:49.176 --> 08:52.605
I am so sorry.

08:52.606 --> 08:56.034
Well, bad news is no stranger
when you have a body like mine.

08:56.035 --> 08:57.652
I know where I am.

08:57.653 --> 08:59.629
Which is why I'm here.

08:59.630 --> 09:01.464
I want to do something crazy

09:01.465 --> 09:03.157
with the little time I have left.

09:03.158 --> 09:05.775
What are you planning, Finn?

09:05.776 --> 09:07.710
(PHONE BUZZING)

09:14.127 --> 09:16.680
- Hey. <i>
- Hey.</i>

09:16.681 --> 09:19.015
One of your favorite
patients is here. Finn Niver.

09:19.016 --> 09:21.582
- How is he? <i>
- As feisty as ever.</i>

09:21.583 --> 09:23.157
But, um...

09:23.158 --> 09:25.033
This is the end, isn't it?

09:25.034 --> 09:27.892
(SIGHS) Yeah.

09:27.893 --> 09:29.865
I need to see him.

09:29.866 --> 09:31.680
Well, that can be arranged.

09:31.681 --> 09:33.872
You know I can't set foot inside there.

09:33.873 --> 09:35.196
<i>Well, not at Chastain.</i>

09:35.197 --> 09:37.167
<i>There's something that Finn wants to do,</i>

09:37.168 --> 09:39.168
<i>and he needs a doctor to do it with him.</i>

09:43.699 --> 09:45.342
I'm listening.

09:45.343 --> 09:48.177
How do you feel about space travel?

09:54.167 --> 09:55.852
(ELECTRIC CHAIR WHIRRING)

09:55.853 --> 09:58.188
(FINN CHUCKLES)

09:58.189 --> 10:00.715
FINN: You eat, sleep,
and breathe this place,

10:00.716 --> 10:02.215
and the day I need you most,

10:02.216 --> 10:04.023
I find out you don't work here anymore?

10:04.024 --> 10:05.051
What happened?

10:05.052 --> 10:08.688
Ah, it's a long story, Finn.

10:08.689 --> 10:10.655
Someone was a bit

10:10.656 --> 10:13.111
cagey on the phone about
why I'm needed, so...

10:13.112 --> 10:16.397
All I said was it's a
beautiful day to ditch gravity.

10:16.398 --> 10:17.840
Good one. Nice work, Nevin.

10:17.841 --> 10:19.849
What are we talking about? Skydiving?

10:19.850 --> 10:22.505
Hell no. I have been tied to this chair

10:22.506 --> 10:24.616
since I was five years old; I want out.

10:24.617 --> 10:27.908
I want to fly. I want to
float like I own the place.

10:27.909 --> 10:29.702
In zero-g.

10:29.703 --> 10:31.221
Zero gravity?

10:31.222 --> 10:32.980
I sent a pandering letter to the company

10:32.981 --> 10:34.443
that does zero-g flights,

10:34.444 --> 10:37.394
and they gifted tickets for
me and a doctor of my choosing.

10:37.395 --> 10:38.814
So, you in?

10:38.815 --> 10:41.140
Guys...

10:41.141 --> 10:43.683
it is definitely crazy.

10:43.684 --> 10:45.716
Which is exactly why I'm in!

10:45.717 --> 10:47.792
Yes! Oh, let's do it.

10:51.127 --> 10:54.769
I know this is as much
for me as it is for Finn,

10:54.770 --> 10:57.446
and... I appreciate it.

10:57.447 --> 11:00.206
I had nothing to do with
it. It was all Finn's idea.

11:03.754 --> 11:05.421
- Have fun.
- (PAGER BEEPING)

11:09.743 --> 11:12.212
Mom calls them brain damage on wheels.

11:12.213 --> 11:14.412
In her ICU in Boston,
a quarter of the beds

11:14.413 --> 11:16.138
are always filled with scooter patients.

11:16.139 --> 11:18.782
- So I got off easy?
- Because you were wearing a helmet.

11:19.937 --> 11:21.604
So, how's it going with Odel?

11:21.605 --> 11:22.755
He really wanted answers,

11:22.756 --> 11:24.393
so I called Pulmonology for a consult.

11:24.394 --> 11:26.180
Dr. Langford recommended a bronchoscopy

11:26.181 --> 11:27.944
- just to be sure.
- He has a cough

11:27.945 --> 11:29.854
with clear lungs and
a normal chest X-ray.

11:29.855 --> 11:31.494
He didn't need a Pulmonology consult.

11:31.495 --> 11:32.679
EZRA: The patient wanted one.

11:32.680 --> 11:34.584
And he's about to travel.
I was in Nairobi once,

11:34.585 --> 11:36.962
- caught this nasty parasite and, um...
- Both of you, follow me.

11:36.963 --> 11:38.188
Okay.

11:39.940 --> 11:41.315
(MONITOR BEEPING STEADILY)

11:41.316 --> 11:43.293
Well, guess we're too late.

11:43.294 --> 11:45.151
Can I help you with
something, Dr. Pravesh?

11:45.152 --> 11:46.861
This procedure is unnecessary.

11:46.862 --> 11:48.798
Step out, please.
This is now my patient.

11:48.799 --> 11:50.116
- (COUGHING)
- (ALARM BEEPING)

11:50.117 --> 11:53.067
O2 sat is dropping.

11:53.068 --> 11:54.453
He's aspirating.

11:54.454 --> 11:56.664
Turn up the suction. Get him on 100% O2

11:56.665 --> 11:58.958
and abort the bronch.

11:58.959 --> 12:01.052
- Wh-What's happening?
- He's choking on his own vomit.

12:01.053 --> 12:03.054
No invasive procedure
is completely safe.

12:03.055 --> 12:05.673
You have to weigh the
danger of a simple cough

12:05.674 --> 12:09.234
against an unintended
consequence like this one.

12:10.321 --> 12:12.321
Yikes.

12:17.995 --> 12:20.071
He's stable.

12:20.072 --> 12:21.814
- That's something.
- But he has to be admitted.

12:21.815 --> 12:23.160
He's on supplemental oxygen

12:23.161 --> 12:24.726
and will need antibiotics to treat

12:24.727 --> 12:28.269
the aspiration pneumonia caused
by an unnecessary bronchoscopy.

12:28.270 --> 12:31.375
He wanted answers. I consulted
an experienced pulmonologist

12:31.376 --> 12:32.750
who suggested the bronchoscopy.

12:32.751 --> 12:34.868
Which is a relatively benign procedure

12:34.869 --> 12:36.409
- with good diagnostic yield.
- Stop.

12:37.681 --> 12:39.331
It's simple.

12:39.332 --> 12:40.374
You made a mistake.

12:40.375 --> 12:42.093
You need to accept responsibility,

12:42.094 --> 12:44.520
learn and move on.

12:47.719 --> 12:49.268
You read Annie Diamonte's chart?

12:49.269 --> 12:51.177
Yes. I recommend

12:51.178 --> 12:53.053
you start with the good
news and finish with the bad.

12:53.054 --> 12:55.322
Well, I prefer to close on the positive.

12:58.444 --> 13:00.352
- Hey.
- Hey.

13:00.353 --> 13:02.539
You know, we really have
to stop meeting like this.

13:02.540 --> 13:06.042
You know, as much as I enjoy
seeing you, Annie, I agree.

13:06.043 --> 13:08.152
I was really hoping that last chest tube

13:08.153 --> 13:09.620
would have taken care of it,

13:09.621 --> 13:11.714
but your CT scan shows
that you still have

13:11.715 --> 13:13.049
what's called an empyema,

13:13.050 --> 13:15.218
an infection between
your lung and your chest,

13:15.219 --> 13:17.036
which is what's causing your fevers.

13:17.037 --> 13:19.222
But there's good news.

13:19.223 --> 13:20.764
We saw your scan...

13:21.852 --> 13:23.584
... and no sign of cancer.

13:23.585 --> 13:25.878
The immunotherapy is working.

13:25.879 --> 13:27.230
What?

13:27.231 --> 13:28.829
My cancer's gone?

13:28.830 --> 13:30.279
(CHUCKLES): Yeah.

13:30.280 --> 13:32.360
Well, you know, you really
should have led with that.

13:33.489 --> 13:37.114
I was gonna tell you to stop
the drugs and let me go.

13:40.077 --> 13:42.912
(CRYING)

13:42.913 --> 13:45.214
(EXHALES) So... so what's the plan?

13:45.215 --> 13:47.847
I mean, another chest
tube? New antibiotic?

13:47.848 --> 13:49.568
Well, we are actually
here to talk to you

13:49.569 --> 13:52.071
about another option. A decortication.

13:52.072 --> 13:54.907
We open your chest, then
we clear the infection,

13:54.908 --> 13:57.260
and we scrape off the peel
that's trapping your lung,

13:57.261 --> 13:59.177
which is what's making it
hard for you to breathe.

13:59.178 --> 14:01.080
What could go wrong?

14:01.081 --> 14:02.265
NIC: Plenty.

14:02.266 --> 14:03.940
This is a very high-risk surgery.

14:03.941 --> 14:05.709
There's a high likelihood of bleeding,

14:05.710 --> 14:07.666
which could be catastrophic,

14:07.667 --> 14:09.237
particularly given the trauma

14:09.238 --> 14:10.940
you've already been
through from the explosion.

14:10.941 --> 14:13.092
And even if Dr. Austin

14:13.093 --> 14:15.278
is able to do the surgery successfully,

14:15.279 --> 14:17.988
your lung may never reexpand.

14:22.038 --> 14:23.987
What are my alternatives?

14:23.988 --> 14:26.605
I mean, I live my life
in and out of here,

14:26.606 --> 14:29.700
sick and in limbo,
buy my time till I die?

14:29.701 --> 14:31.328
I can't do that.

14:31.329 --> 14:34.321
(CRYING): And if my
cancer's in remission,

14:34.322 --> 14:36.673
I have a shot at getting my life back.

14:38.285 --> 14:40.828
You do understand the risks of surgery?

14:40.829 --> 14:42.472
Yeah. Well, whatever they are,

14:42.473 --> 14:45.124
I'll take my chances. (CHUCKLES)

14:45.125 --> 14:47.768
Oh, wow.

14:49.347 --> 14:51.722
<i>... for yourself or for someone else,</i>

14:51.723 --> 14:53.500
<i>this is something...</i>

14:53.501 --> 14:55.508
I'm gone a matter of weeks,

14:55.509 --> 14:57.474
you're in the servants' quarters,

14:57.475 --> 15:01.491
and my son, one of the best
doctors at Chastain, is fired?

15:01.492 --> 15:03.159
I'm not responsible for that.

15:03.160 --> 15:04.967
Obviously.

15:04.968 --> 15:07.257
Conrad is dodging my calls.

15:07.258 --> 15:09.574
His way of asking me to stand down.

15:09.575 --> 15:12.374
- Hmm. Well, stand down.
- My lawyers are submitting

15:12.375 --> 15:13.970
a whistleblower suit.

15:13.971 --> 15:16.863
You know how many are filed every year?

15:16.864 --> 15:19.917
Whistleblower protection
is a joke in Georgia.

15:19.918 --> 15:21.483
I'll tell you what'll happen.

15:21.484 --> 15:24.330
Red Rock will sue you for
libel, and they may win.

15:24.331 --> 15:27.514
So I'm taking advice from
a guy who's lost two jobs

15:27.515 --> 15:28.841
- in two weeks?
- Yeah.

15:28.842 --> 15:31.095
Being demoted by these
people is an honor.

15:31.096 --> 15:33.339
How do we fight back?

15:33.340 --> 15:35.858
Well, you got a slingshot?

15:35.859 --> 15:38.608
Look, all due respect, don't
go down that path until you have

15:38.609 --> 15:40.976
- a bulletproof strategy.
- Oh, I've got one.

15:45.450 --> 15:47.617
Well, if you're hell-bent
on moving forward,

15:47.618 --> 15:49.216
then I suggest...

15:49.217 --> 15:51.860
you have a look at Logan Kim.

15:53.234 --> 15:55.085
Thanks.

16:00.867 --> 16:02.983
Dr. Austin.

16:02.984 --> 16:04.975
Watch the coat. It's custom.

16:04.976 --> 16:06.967
I don't like wrinkles.

16:06.968 --> 16:10.068
Well, here's one. I'm
reviewing mortality outcomes

16:10.069 --> 16:13.045
of all surgeons, and you're an outlier.

16:13.046 --> 16:14.805
Your stats aren't up to par.

16:14.806 --> 16:17.066
And as chief, your outcomes
are now my outcomes.

16:17.067 --> 16:20.293
Come on, bruh. Everybody knows
that my outcomes are excellent

16:20.294 --> 16:21.963
for the kind of cases I take.

16:21.964 --> 16:24.765
My patients are the
sickest. My surgeries, risky.

16:24.766 --> 16:26.088
Which is precisely my point.

16:26.089 --> 16:28.884
Annie Diamonte's upcoming surgery
is too much of a long shot.

16:28.885 --> 16:30.729
- You need to reassess.
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.

16:30.730 --> 16:32.156
Hold up.

16:32.157 --> 16:35.826
You don't want me to do a
highly profitable procedure?

16:35.827 --> 16:38.235
- The crème de la crème of RVUs?
- I'm only suggesting

16:38.236 --> 16:39.780
that you have a plan B.

16:39.781 --> 16:41.573
An escape hatch, so to speak.

16:41.574 --> 16:44.335
Oh. So if something
catastrophic were to happen,

16:44.336 --> 16:46.412
you want me to keep
her alive at all costs,

16:46.413 --> 16:48.070
not let her die on my table,

16:48.071 --> 16:49.906
- just to pad my stats.
- What I'm saying to you,

16:49.907 --> 16:52.292
Dr. Austin, is that your statistics

16:52.293 --> 16:54.574
don't meet what I
expect from my surgeons.

16:54.575 --> 16:57.579
So, yes, you keep her alive at all costs

16:57.580 --> 17:00.015
and don't mention a DNR to your patient.

17:12.108 --> 17:14.638
As the plane descends, we'll
vary the flight profiles

17:14.640 --> 17:16.603
so you can feel the
weightlessness of both martian

17:16.604 --> 17:17.818
and lunar gravity.

17:17.819 --> 17:19.127
So this isn't a free fall.

17:19.128 --> 17:20.654
That's Kimmy.

17:20.655 --> 17:23.374
She makes these crazy
videos in the best way.

17:23.375 --> 17:25.451
She may be a living emoji. (CHUCKLES)

17:25.452 --> 17:27.136
- Shh.
- SAFETY COORDINATOR: You'll also experience...

17:27.137 --> 17:28.638
And that's Reggie Perez.

17:28.639 --> 17:31.991
Retired Atlanta United
defender, 2015 to 2017.

17:31.992 --> 17:34.385
CONRAD: Hey, you're in good company, Finn,
but they got nothing on you.

17:34.386 --> 17:35.961
You're the real badass here.

17:35.962 --> 17:38.222
Don't ever forget that.

17:38.223 --> 17:40.149
SAFETY COORDINATOR: You'll
experience 15 simulations

17:40.150 --> 17:43.302
in total in increments
of about 30 seconds a pop.

17:43.303 --> 17:45.804
Most people think that
zero-g is only experienced

17:45.805 --> 17:48.348
- when the plane is in a dive.
- Hey, Reggie.

17:48.349 --> 17:50.742
Yeah.

17:51.811 --> 17:53.802
I was MVP of the Golden Kickers

17:53.803 --> 17:55.665
till my career ended at age five.

17:55.666 --> 17:58.484
But mini-me could have
taken mini-you down.

17:58.485 --> 18:00.050
I don't doubt it for a second, bud.

18:00.051 --> 18:02.004
Well, once we're weightless,
it's an even playing field,

18:02.005 --> 18:03.645
and I am coming for you.

18:03.646 --> 18:06.033
(LAUGHS) And I'm scared.

18:06.034 --> 18:08.535
I'll see you out there.

18:08.536 --> 18:10.370
He said he's scared.

18:10.371 --> 18:11.997
Does he look scared?

18:11.998 --> 18:13.731
No.

18:13.732 --> 18:15.709
SAFETY COORDINATOR: Of course
all the rush and excitement

18:15.710 --> 18:17.169
- come with perils, like nausea.
- (CHUCKLES)

18:17.170 --> 18:19.021
It's called vomit comet for a reason.

18:19.022 --> 18:21.856
But there are also other
risks, including dizziness,

18:21.857 --> 18:23.192
fluctuating blood pressure.

18:23.193 --> 18:26.341
There are very rare but
very real complications

18:26.342 --> 18:28.486
aside from the vomit issue, of course...

18:28.487 --> 18:31.442
Are <i> you</i> scared?

18:31.443 --> 18:34.843
You can change your mind.
It's totally fine if you are.

18:34.844 --> 18:36.577
It's not, really.

18:36.578 --> 18:38.668
'Cause then I'm gonna
spend the rest of my life

18:38.669 --> 18:40.618
wondering "what if".

18:40.619 --> 18:43.713
Means my final weeks would be
torture, and I can't do that.

18:43.714 --> 18:45.709
SAFETY COORDINATOR: We'll
take those signed waivers now,

18:45.710 --> 18:47.741
because it's time for zero-g, people.

18:47.742 --> 18:50.719
- (CHEERING, APPLAUSE)
- (LAUGHS)

18:55.583 --> 18:57.894
One thing, though, doc.

18:57.895 --> 19:00.369
I know you've been through a lot lately,

19:00.370 --> 19:02.972
and I don't want to make it worse.

19:04.365 --> 19:07.223
Listen, if things go south up there...

19:07.224 --> 19:08.866
like really south...

19:10.482 --> 19:12.099
... don't blame yourself, okay?

19:12.100 --> 19:15.486
I mean, the worst that
happens up there is I die.

19:15.487 --> 19:18.371
And is zero-g really
the worst way to go?

19:19.825 --> 19:21.750
No, it isn't.

19:27.237 --> 19:29.908
We obviously want the
surgery to be a success.

19:29.909 --> 19:33.262
But it's risky. So we have to ask

19:33.263 --> 19:35.172
have you thought about

19:35.173 --> 19:37.457
what you want if things don't go well?

19:37.458 --> 19:41.103
I've thought about it a lot
since the cancer diagnosis.

19:41.104 --> 19:43.848
You know, I-I love the outdoors

19:43.849 --> 19:46.684
and the physical challenges.

19:46.685 --> 19:50.469
A life hooked up to a machine
is no life at all for me.

19:50.470 --> 19:53.703
So if that is my only choice,

19:53.704 --> 19:55.805
I want you to let me go.

19:56.954 --> 19:59.196
AUSTIN: Okay.

19:59.197 --> 20:02.199
Well, then let's fill out
a Do Not Resuscitate order,

20:02.200 --> 20:04.627
specifying your wishes

20:04.628 --> 20:06.461
so that everyone follows them.

20:11.784 --> 20:14.302
Before I sign that, can I have a minute?

20:16.456 --> 20:18.390
Sure.

20:25.557 --> 20:27.482
- (PHONE VIBRATING)
- (INDISTINCT VIDEO PLAYING)

20:38.905 --> 20:41.906
Hey. Nic filled me in. I'm
really sorry I'm not there.

20:41.907 --> 20:45.817
Yeah. I heard hints as to why
that is, and I don't like it.

20:45.818 --> 20:49.413
<i>- Conrad, are you okay?</i>
- Right now, yeah.

20:49.414 --> 20:52.842
How are you? I hear cancer-free.

20:52.843 --> 20:54.599
- (CHUCKLES) Yeah. <i>
- That's amazing.</i>

20:54.600 --> 20:56.345
It is.

20:56.346 --> 20:59.154
Look, I know you're not
gonna sugarcoat this.

20:59.155 --> 21:00.713
That's why I called you, Conrad.

21:01.834 --> 21:04.044
I'm not sure I can do this.

21:04.045 --> 21:08.024
<i>Yeah, it's risky, and
I'm scared as hell.</i>

21:08.025 --> 21:10.884
- I know that.
- (VIDEO CONTINUING INDISTINCTLY)

21:10.885 --> 21:14.436
I also know it takes a
special kind of superpower

21:14.437 --> 21:16.964
to run into a fire to save a hospital

21:16.965 --> 21:20.611
and kick cancer's ass
all in the same year.

21:20.612 --> 21:23.280
So if anyone's got this,

21:23.281 --> 21:24.623
<i>it's you.</i>

21:26.859 --> 21:30.120
Thanks, Conrad. I really
needed to hear that.

21:30.121 --> 21:31.504
<i>Bye.</i>

21:34.909 --> 21:36.719
- (MONITORS BEEPING)
- (WHEEZING, GASPING)

21:36.720 --> 21:38.077
What's going on?

21:38.078 --> 21:40.646
He was midway through the cefepime
when he started to get wheezy.

21:40.647 --> 21:41.754
Now he can't breathe.

21:41.755 --> 21:44.727
- Sounds like anaphylaxis.
- A reaction to the antibiotics.

21:44.728 --> 21:47.369
Push 0.5 of epinephrine I.M.
now and prepare an epi drip.

21:47.370 --> 21:49.394
- And call the code team.
- (STRAINING): Help me.

21:49.395 --> 21:52.092
We got you, buddy.

21:52.093 --> 21:54.570
- DEVON: Hang in there.
- (RAPID BEEPING)

21:54.571 --> 21:56.430
- Pressure's dropping.
- DEVON: Let's go, let's go, let's go.

21:56.431 --> 21:57.907
Let's get the pads on him. now.

21:57.908 --> 21:59.866
Come on.

22:01.102 --> 22:02.578
Run the code.

22:02.579 --> 22:05.322
What? No, I-I ca-I can't.

22:05.323 --> 22:07.439
(FLATLINING)

22:07.440 --> 22:08.660
We lost his pulse.

22:08.661 --> 22:10.709
Starting compressions.

22:10.710 --> 22:12.755
DEVON: This is your
patient. You made the call.

22:12.756 --> 22:13.756
Run the code.

22:15.408 --> 22:17.524
What's the first question
you ask in a code?

22:17.525 --> 22:19.683
What was the rhythm before he arrested?

22:19.684 --> 22:21.924
- It was PEA.
- What's the differential for a PEA arrest?

22:22.659 --> 22:24.176
- Eline!
- I can't.

22:25.925 --> 22:27.290
Step aside.

22:27.291 --> 22:28.498
Hold compressions.

22:29.960 --> 22:31.450
He's still in PEA.

22:31.451 --> 22:33.093
Restart compressions. Push 1 of epi.

22:36.728 --> 22:38.945
Let's move. I'll intubate.

22:44.195 --> 22:46.480
(GRUNTS)

22:46.481 --> 22:47.789
(WHISPERS INDISTINCTLY)

22:51.346 --> 22:53.653
- I'll get the printout.
- He looks better.

22:53.654 --> 22:55.639
Epi usually works
quickly when you give it,

22:55.640 --> 22:57.051
but his blood pressure's still low.

22:57.052 --> 22:58.702
- Is that real?
- DEVON: Maybe.

22:58.703 --> 23:00.325
But the monitor's just a tool.

23:00.326 --> 23:02.464
I'll need an EKG to know for sure.

23:02.465 --> 23:05.467
I mean, what happened back
there? You just froze up.

23:05.468 --> 23:07.544
(SIGHS) Call a Code STEMI.

23:07.545 --> 23:09.568
Get him to the cath lab now.
He's having a heart attack.

23:09.569 --> 23:12.372
- What just happened?
- It's called a clinical cascade.

23:12.373 --> 23:13.826
When one unnecessary procedure

23:13.827 --> 23:15.677
leads to many more,
increasing the risk of harm

23:15.678 --> 23:18.353
- from complications.
- Which I put into motion.

23:18.354 --> 23:20.547
You couldn't have known he'd
be allergic to the antibiotics.

23:20.548 --> 23:22.505
- That's not her fault.
- From the time a patient comes in

23:22.506 --> 23:23.697
to the time he is discharged,

23:23.698 --> 23:24.722
he is in your hands.

23:24.723 --> 23:26.217
This man came in with a cough, and now

23:26.218 --> 23:28.682
- he might die of a heart attack.
- I will no longer be a doctor.

23:28.683 --> 23:30.549
Not exactly. You're
cheap labor and Red Rock

23:30.550 --> 23:32.853
- will be very forgiving.
- EZRA: Uh, Dr. Pravesh?

23:32.854 --> 23:35.138
Do you have allergies too?

23:35.139 --> 23:36.531
Your neck.

23:40.528 --> 23:42.495
(GRUNTS SOFTLY)

23:52.918 --> 23:57.503
_

24:05.628 --> 24:07.344
- Ah.
- Slow down, Turbo.

24:07.345 --> 24:10.349
Oh, I'm very close to injecting
caffeine directly into my veins.

24:10.350 --> 24:12.190
When do humans figure out the difference

24:12.191 --> 24:14.789
between night and day?
Because Adaku's baby hasn't.

24:14.790 --> 24:17.629
She was fully awake
from 2:00 to 7:00 a.m.,

24:17.630 --> 24:19.095
just staring at me.

24:19.096 --> 24:20.429
Until I tried to put her down.

24:20.430 --> 24:21.598
Then she wails like a banshee.

24:21.599 --> 24:23.190
And she's supposed to
eat every two hours,

24:23.191 --> 24:25.558
but what does she do
almost every single time?

24:25.559 --> 24:27.700
Chucks it up.

24:27.701 --> 24:29.343
Have you tried cuddling?

24:31.688 --> 24:33.679
- What?
- Eating, bathing, sleeping...

24:33.680 --> 24:36.129
it's all secondary to the snuggle.

24:36.130 --> 24:38.480
It affects babies on a molecular level.

24:38.481 --> 24:41.302
Literally changing
their DNA for the better.

24:41.303 --> 24:43.735
It improves their neural
development, their IQ...

24:43.736 --> 24:46.997
I got it. Fine. I'll snuggle.

24:46.998 --> 24:48.840
See you in there.

24:50.910 --> 24:54.763
(WATER RUNNING, STOPS)

24:54.764 --> 24:58.267
Logan Kim. Marshall Winthrop.

24:58.268 --> 24:59.601
I know who you are.

24:59.602 --> 25:02.679
We both know why my son Conrad

25:02.680 --> 25:04.756
was kicked out of Chastain.

25:04.757 --> 25:06.758
He tried to do the right thing,

25:06.759 --> 25:08.259
so you set out to ruin him.

25:08.260 --> 25:10.020
I'm sorry.

25:10.021 --> 25:11.462
Who are you?

25:11.463 --> 25:13.765
I believe we've already covered that.

25:13.766 --> 25:15.433
No, I mean, who are you, really...

25:15.434 --> 25:17.559
the good guy you're
now pretending to be,

25:17.560 --> 25:19.745
or the world heavyweight
champion of hypocrites?

25:20.999 --> 25:22.815
I'm here to talk about my son.

25:22.816 --> 25:24.555
Take your grievance elsewhere.

25:24.556 --> 25:26.986
You think you can muscle me
with your power and fortune,

25:26.987 --> 25:28.780
but I know how you made that fortune,

25:28.781 --> 25:31.616
and it wasn't through
random acts of kindness.

25:31.617 --> 25:34.776
To get on your high horse,
it was kill or be killed.

25:34.777 --> 25:36.453
This isn't about <i> me.</i>

25:37.307 --> 25:39.664
I'm making it about you.

25:39.665 --> 25:41.189
James Willebrand.

25:41.190 --> 25:43.104
COO of one of your first companies.

25:43.105 --> 25:44.837
FCC came sniffing around.

25:44.838 --> 25:48.317
But you made sure he paid
dearly for ratting you out.

25:48.318 --> 25:50.152
See, I know where the bodies are buried.

25:50.153 --> 25:52.896
And I will dig them up to
stink in the light of day

25:52.897 --> 25:54.397
and bring you to your aging knees

25:54.398 --> 25:56.616
if you ever challenge me again.

25:58.686 --> 26:00.286
Don't tempt me.

26:05.668 --> 26:07.084
♪♪

26:11.629 --> 26:13.396
<i>PILOT (ON SPEAKER):
Climbing to 20 degrees.</i>

26:15.511 --> 26:17.652
This is seriously weird.

26:17.653 --> 26:20.795
<i>- Thirty.</i>
- Pretty sure it's about to get weirder.

26:20.796 --> 26:23.079
<i>Forty.</i>

26:23.080 --> 26:25.762
<i>Zero gravity.</i>

26:25.763 --> 26:29.024
♪♪

26:29.025 --> 26:31.693
Oh, hello freedom.

26:31.694 --> 26:33.486
(LAUGHS)

26:34.847 --> 26:38.108
<i>♪ Out here in the fields ♪</i>

26:38.109 --> 26:41.370
- <i>♪ I fight for my meals ♪</i>
- (LAUGHS)

26:41.371 --> 26:43.896
Yeah!

26:43.897 --> 26:47.667
<i>♪ I get my back into my living ♪</i>

26:52.072 --> 26:53.589
<i>♪ I don't need to fight ♪</i>

26:56.174 --> 26:58.475
<i>♪ To prove I'm right ♪</i>

27:00.458 --> 27:04.202
<i>♪ I don't need to be forgiven ♪</i>

27:04.203 --> 27:07.922
<i>♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah ♪</i>

27:08.842 --> 27:09.949
Hey, Reggie.

27:09.950 --> 27:11.166
Yeah?

27:11.167 --> 27:12.717
Bet you can't do this.

27:14.472 --> 27:15.997
(LAUGHS)

27:15.998 --> 27:17.832
I'll bet you're right. (CHUCKLES)

27:17.833 --> 27:20.144
(FINN LAUGHING)

27:20.145 --> 27:23.338
(GRUNTING)

27:23.339 --> 27:24.890
Oh...

27:24.891 --> 27:26.816
(GRUNTING CONTINUES)

27:36.995 --> 27:38.661
(LAUGHS)

27:40.031 --> 27:41.573
I'm messing with you, Hawkins.

27:41.574 --> 27:43.333
- Aw...
- I'm sorry.

27:43.334 --> 27:44.990
I-I've been planning that one all day,

27:44.991 --> 27:46.670
but you should've seen your face.

27:46.671 --> 27:49.420
(LAUGHING) You got me.

27:49.421 --> 27:51.324
- You got me.
- He got you good.

27:51.325 --> 27:53.311
Aw, you got me!

27:53.312 --> 27:54.494
(LAUGHING)

27:54.495 --> 27:56.329
See you sometime.

27:56.330 --> 27:57.705
(BOTH LAUGHING)

27:57.706 --> 28:00.516
MINA: Scalpel.

28:03.264 --> 28:05.047
I-I can't see where to start cutting.

28:05.048 --> 28:06.880
All right. Let's turn the lung over
and go to the other side.

28:06.881 --> 28:10.184
Agreed. Now, Mina,
grab the peel with a hemostat.

28:10.185 --> 28:12.628
Make sure you use the
blunt end of the forceps.

28:13.514 --> 28:17.460
Okay. I got it. I see
healthy lung underneath.

28:17.461 --> 28:19.536
AUSTIN: You know, Cain
was breathing down my neck

28:19.537 --> 28:21.062
about my stats earlier.

28:21.063 --> 28:23.253
He told me to keep
Annie alive at all costs.

28:23.254 --> 28:25.202
Must be an open bed at the vent farm.

28:25.735 --> 28:28.192
- What's that?
- MINA: Atlanta Promised Care.

28:28.193 --> 28:31.463
That's where he sends
all his... "saves".

28:31.464 --> 28:34.023
AUSTIN: Oh, so that's
how he keeps his stats up

28:34.024 --> 28:36.782
and the money flowing. His escape hatch.

28:36.783 --> 28:39.544
- That's one point of view.
- Is there another?

28:39.545 --> 28:41.666
NOLAN: Well, for every ten
patients we send to APC,

28:41.667 --> 28:43.572
maybe one might make it home.

28:43.573 --> 28:45.531
Those aren't great numbers,
but it's a chance, right?

28:45.532 --> 28:48.299
But for Cain, that's not what
it's about and you know it.

28:48.300 --> 28:49.791
- NOLAN: Ah!
- MINA: Damn it.

28:49.792 --> 28:51.377
- A bleeder.
- AUSTIN: Hey, Chu,

28:51.378 --> 28:52.882
you get to work on her pressure, man.

28:52.883 --> 28:54.843
And order up some more
blood. We're gonna need it.

28:58.979 --> 29:01.292
MINA: There's too much
bleeding. I can't see.

29:01.293 --> 29:03.284
- Chu, hang another unit, please.
- I've already used everything

29:03.285 --> 29:04.957
we have up here, another
cooler's on the way.

29:04.958 --> 29:06.023
AUSTIN: Suction.

29:06.024 --> 29:07.268
Should we inflate the lung again?

29:07.269 --> 29:08.269
No, it's not gonna help.

29:11.708 --> 29:13.107
If-if she codes...

29:13.108 --> 29:16.253
You let her go. To hell with Cain.

29:16.254 --> 29:19.279
- But that's not gonna happen because...
- MINA: You have a plan.

29:19.280 --> 29:20.732
AUSTIN: Of course I have a plan.

29:20.733 --> 29:22.259
There's too much damage to the lung.

29:22.260 --> 29:23.652
We need to remove the whole lobe.

29:23.653 --> 29:25.503
Is that gonna leave her
with enough lung function?

29:25.504 --> 29:27.430
It better. Let's get to work.

29:36.274 --> 29:38.748
- Pressure's stable.
- AUSTIN: (SIGHS) Good deal.

29:38.749 --> 29:40.593
All right, Dr. Okafor. It's all you.

29:40.594 --> 29:42.470
- Show me what you got.
- With pleasure.

29:42.471 --> 29:43.930
<i>(CONRAD WHOOPING)</i>

29:43.931 --> 29:45.421
Oh, yeah!

29:45.422 --> 29:47.755
Ooh, nice one, Hawkins.

29:47.756 --> 29:48.756
You okay, man?

29:51.222 --> 29:52.655
Reggie, can you hear me?

29:57.945 --> 30:00.538
Tell the pilot to level out.

30:00.539 --> 30:02.874
Reggie's in cardiac arrest.
We need a defibrillator.

30:02.875 --> 30:04.273
MAN: Captain, we have...

30:04.274 --> 30:06.263
Flip upside down and put
your feet up on the wall.

30:06.264 --> 30:07.304
Over here!

30:07.305 --> 30:08.929
We need a defibrillator.

30:14.628 --> 30:15.948
CONRAD: Let's hold him down.

30:16.882 --> 30:18.807
Here we go.

30:19.392 --> 30:21.150
(GRUNTING)

30:28.009 --> 30:29.669
<i>PILOT: Returning to Earth's gravity now.</i>

30:31.496 --> 30:32.870
Conrad.

30:38.954 --> 30:40.453
Clear.

30:40.454 --> 30:42.088
(BEEPING)

30:44.842 --> 30:46.774
(COUGHING)

30:46.775 --> 30:49.817
You're good. You're good.

30:49.818 --> 30:51.285
He's back.

30:52.740 --> 30:54.256
FINN: We did it. (LAUGHS)

31:00.728 --> 31:04.051
<i>- DOCTOR: Deploying the stent.</i>
- Odel's clogged artery

31:04.052 --> 31:06.935
is about to be opened, and this cascade

31:06.936 --> 31:10.224
will transform into more of a trickle.

31:10.225 --> 31:12.708
If he'd gone to a Cambodian
doctor in a village,

31:12.709 --> 31:14.853
they would've given him a
tea and sent him on his way.

31:14.854 --> 31:16.687
Instead he came here with a cough

31:16.688 --> 31:18.271
and I gave him a heart attack.

31:19.576 --> 31:21.641
And that is what's gonna
make you a good doctor.

31:21.642 --> 31:22.867
Giving patients heart attacks?

31:24.008 --> 31:25.039
Humility.

31:25.040 --> 31:26.748
Acceptance.

31:26.749 --> 31:28.967
Those are the main
ingredients in being one.

31:31.046 --> 31:34.205
He might have coronary artery
disease that was undiagnosed

31:34.206 --> 31:36.458
and exacerbated during zero-g.

31:36.459 --> 31:40.118
Tell Dr. Feldman to give
cardiology a heads-up

31:40.119 --> 31:42.887
- that a V fib arrest with ROSC is coming in.
- Copy that.

31:46.102 --> 31:48.028
Reggie's gonna be okay, right?

31:48.029 --> 31:49.386
I believe so.

31:49.387 --> 31:51.679
FINN: 'Cause, you know, I'd feel weird

31:51.680 --> 31:53.534
talking about how insanely awesome

31:53.535 --> 31:56.203
- (CHUCKLING)
- that zero-g experience was, right, if...

31:56.204 --> 31:58.688
He's in great hands. It's not weird.

31:58.689 --> 32:02.117
Oh, dude, how freaking cool was that?!

32:02.118 --> 32:04.119
(BOTH CHUCKLING)

32:04.120 --> 32:06.236
I believed you when you
said we'd be floating,

32:06.237 --> 32:07.548
but I guess I didn't really believe you,

32:07.549 --> 32:09.407
because when we started to rise up...

32:09.408 --> 32:11.044
You-you almost peed yourself?

32:11.045 --> 32:13.721
- (CHUCKLING) Yeah. Yeah.
- Yeah, me too!

32:13.722 --> 32:15.631
Except for me wouldn't be
the first time, so no biggie,

32:15.632 --> 32:17.224
but that was incredible.

32:17.225 --> 32:19.723
Yeah. Yeah, it was. Thank you

32:19.724 --> 32:23.254
for dragging me out there.
I really needed this badly.

32:23.255 --> 32:25.148
Oh.

32:28.464 --> 32:31.647
Hey. You okay, man?

32:31.648 --> 32:34.032
I mean, really.

32:36.268 --> 32:38.578
I was so happy.

32:42.210 --> 32:46.111
I had my work and the most
amazing woman in my life.

32:46.112 --> 32:49.164
They gave me purpose.

32:49.165 --> 32:51.883
I don't know who I am right now.

32:54.837 --> 32:57.805
Or who I'll be if I
can't be a doctor anymore.

32:58.841 --> 33:01.241
I do know

33:01.242 --> 33:03.067
whatever that version of me

33:03.068 --> 33:05.902
looks like, there's no
way Nic deserves that.

33:14.190 --> 33:15.281
No.

33:16.880 --> 33:18.070
No?

33:18.071 --> 33:20.521
No, you cannot let them win.

33:20.522 --> 33:22.379
Medicine is money,

33:22.380 --> 33:24.617
and money breeds jerks.

33:24.618 --> 33:26.442
But you...

33:26.443 --> 33:28.419
you got to knuckle up
and get your job back.

33:29.706 --> 33:32.949
Hey, if not for yourself,

33:32.950 --> 33:35.803
then do it for the patients
who are relying on you.

33:35.804 --> 33:37.328
Get mad.

33:37.329 --> 33:40.331
Go kick some Red Rock ass.

33:40.332 --> 33:42.884
'Cause we are the Zero-G Brothers,

33:42.885 --> 33:46.388
and nobody... and I mean nobody...

33:46.389 --> 33:48.223
can keep us down.

33:48.224 --> 33:51.009
All right?

33:51.010 --> 33:52.568
Zero-G Brothers?

33:54.155 --> 33:55.322
Yeah.

33:55.323 --> 33:59.067
- (CHUCKLES)
- For life.

33:59.068 --> 34:00.518
You know what?

34:00.519 --> 34:01.869
Guys like us...

34:03.832 --> 34:06.541
... find a way to beat the odds.

34:24.351 --> 34:25.710
Don't get too excited.

34:25.710 --> 34:27.688
She'll be off that vent shortly.

34:27.688 --> 34:29.172
So you'll have to find another patient

34:29.172 --> 34:31.024
to fill your open bed.

34:31.025 --> 34:32.791
What's an empty bed cost you...

34:32.792 --> 34:35.103
another overpriced painting?

34:35.103 --> 34:37.387
I remind you that I am the chief.

34:37.388 --> 34:40.080
And with your stats, you're expendable.

34:40.081 --> 34:41.971
Well, I'd like to
remind you of something

34:41.972 --> 34:43.393
you've apparently forgotten.

34:43.395 --> 34:47.524
The sacred contract between
a surgeon and a patient.

34:47.525 --> 34:50.952
That which distinguishes us
from all other physicians.

34:50.953 --> 34:53.862
We cut people open.

34:53.864 --> 34:55.842
We inflict wounds to make them better.

34:55.842 --> 34:58.701
They trust us with their lives.

34:58.702 --> 35:00.703
And I don't cut for the sake of cutting.

35:00.704 --> 35:03.724
I don't do it for the
prestige or the cash

35:03.725 --> 35:06.209
or the stats or the RVUs.

35:06.210 --> 35:08.637
I do it for the patients.

35:08.638 --> 35:11.306
I do it for people like her.

35:11.307 --> 35:13.975
You must have been different once.

35:13.976 --> 35:16.812
What happened to you, Barrett?

35:16.813 --> 35:19.071
I was born the man I am
today, and I'm proud of it.

35:21.433 --> 35:24.578
No. No, I... I think you're lying.

35:24.579 --> 35:26.343
You encouraged this woman to sign a DNR

35:26.344 --> 35:28.086
when I explicitly told you not to.

35:28.607 --> 35:30.083
You will not disobey me again.

35:30.084 --> 35:31.850
Or what?

35:31.851 --> 35:33.714
You'll have me fired, like Hawkins?

35:33.715 --> 35:35.497
Demoted, like Bell?

35:35.498 --> 35:38.425
What's the endgame, Barrett?

35:38.426 --> 35:40.238
You cut all your adversaries,

35:40.239 --> 35:41.792
surround yourself with bootlickers

35:41.793 --> 35:43.570
and those who toe the line.

35:43.571 --> 35:45.312
Yeah, it'll work for a hot minute,

35:45.313 --> 35:48.084
but I guarantee you it
will breed resentment,

35:48.085 --> 35:49.678
corruption.

35:49.679 --> 35:53.440
And eventually Chastain will implode,

35:53.441 --> 35:55.441
and you right along with it.

36:06.835 --> 36:09.419
I told him going to
the ER was a crazy idea.

36:09.420 --> 36:10.913
It's a good thing he didn't listen.

36:10.914 --> 36:12.704
It's just lucky it
happened here at Chastain,

36:12.705 --> 36:15.295
where we have a
world-class cardiac team.

36:15.296 --> 36:16.936
ODEL: That is lucky.

36:16.937 --> 36:18.987
- (COUGHS)
- Honey...

36:18.988 --> 36:21.488
Did the bronchoscopy explain
why I have this damn cough?

36:24.288 --> 36:26.139
Postnasal drip.

36:26.140 --> 36:29.094
Which is what I saw when I
first examined you in the ER.

36:29.095 --> 36:30.886
But we needed the test to confirm that.

36:30.887 --> 36:32.980
Did we?

36:32.981 --> 36:35.505
DEVON: Antihistamines are
the first line of treatment.

36:35.506 --> 36:36.834
If it's still bothering you, I'd say

36:36.835 --> 36:38.318
talk to your primary care doctor.

36:38.319 --> 36:40.303
but there's nothing to worry about.

36:40.304 --> 36:42.472
- See?
- That's good news.

36:42.473 --> 36:45.015
ODEL: Thank you...

36:45.016 --> 36:46.915
for the great care.

36:46.916 --> 36:48.183
Our pleasure.

36:52.223 --> 36:54.030
<i>ELINE: Why didn't you say anything?</i>

36:54.031 --> 36:55.997
He wasn't lucky to have
a heart attack here.

36:55.998 --> 36:57.029
I gave it to him.

36:57.030 --> 36:59.163
It is also my instinct to be truthful,

36:59.164 --> 37:01.439
and I am, most of the time.

37:01.440 --> 37:03.706
- So why not now?
- Because if we tell the truth,

37:03.707 --> 37:04.941
you'll be fired for whistleblowing,

37:04.942 --> 37:06.696
and another conscientious
doctor will no longer

37:06.697 --> 37:08.620
- be helping patients.
- (SIGHS)

37:08.621 --> 37:10.071
The lesson to learn is

37:10.072 --> 37:11.854
the best and hardest thing in medicine

37:11.855 --> 37:14.459
is often to do nothing.

37:14.460 --> 37:16.553
We care for our patients
knowing full well

37:16.554 --> 37:17.963
this is also a business.

37:17.964 --> 37:20.131
The trick is not to get
caught between the two.

37:20.132 --> 37:22.467
My first day was also a disaster.

37:22.468 --> 37:24.584
And by the end of it, I
was questioning whether...

37:24.585 --> 37:26.566
I worked way too hard to get here.

37:26.567 --> 37:28.715
I have no intention of quitting.

37:28.716 --> 37:30.901
Good.

37:30.902 --> 37:33.543
No one died, no one quit.

37:33.544 --> 37:34.544
My job here is done.

37:36.022 --> 37:38.346
Oh, and you're not the only one to blame

37:38.347 --> 37:39.985
for Odel's bronchoscopy.

37:39.986 --> 37:41.894
The new RVU system is, too.

37:41.895 --> 37:44.605
Radical virus...

37:44.606 --> 37:48.418
- Relative value units.
- Oh.

37:48.419 --> 37:51.611
That's why Dr. Langford
was so quick to suggest it.

37:51.612 --> 37:53.871
Right.

37:57.827 --> 37:59.926
- (AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)
- Well, today is the day

37:59.927 --> 38:02.419
we introduce 3B Life
to the American public,

38:02.420 --> 38:05.340
and I'll be damned if
you two handsome bastards

38:05.341 --> 38:06.601
aren't just perfect for the job.

38:06.602 --> 38:08.419
Just, you know, stick
to the teleprompter

38:08.420 --> 38:10.352
and gold we shall be.

38:10.353 --> 38:11.729
As they say on the boards of Broadway,

38:11.730 --> 38:13.372
<i>hatsloche un broche.</i>

38:14.659 --> 38:16.474
Break a leg.

38:16.475 --> 38:18.006
<i>MAN: (OVER INTERCOM) 3B Life,
you're up in one minute.</i>

38:18.007 --> 38:19.449
WOMAN (IN DISTANCE): We
have Dr. Randolph Bell

38:19.450 --> 38:20.951
and Andrea Braydon...

38:20.952 --> 38:24.144
- Ready to make history?
- You bet.

38:24.145 --> 38:26.237
(APPLAUSE)

38:33.464 --> 38:36.299
Hey, how's the big first day?

38:36.300 --> 38:38.951
Mm, practicing medicine is hard,

38:38.952 --> 38:41.379
but teaching it is a whole other beast.

38:41.380 --> 38:43.164
That's the truth.

38:43.165 --> 38:45.216
There's something else. I
need to schedule some lab work.

38:45.217 --> 38:47.168
- Yeah? For who?
- Me.

38:47.169 --> 38:48.694
What's wrong?

38:48.695 --> 38:50.639
I've just got some pain under my ribs.

38:50.640 --> 38:52.725
Stomach ache, and this rash.

38:52.726 --> 38:54.467
And my fingers are...

38:54.468 --> 38:56.820
Hmm, headache? Increased heart rate?

38:56.821 --> 38:58.127
Yeah.

38:58.128 --> 39:01.605
(SIGHS) I think you have RAS.

39:03.281 --> 39:05.363
Resident anxiety syndrome.

39:05.364 --> 39:06.571
(LAUGHS)

39:06.572 --> 39:07.979
Conrad had it, too.

39:07.980 --> 39:09.866
It's the anxiety of being
a second-year resident

39:09.867 --> 39:10.973
responsible for others.

39:10.974 --> 39:12.423
Can't say it ever goes away,

39:12.424 --> 39:14.252
but you do learn to live with it.

39:14.253 --> 39:16.404
- I hope you're right.
- I think I am.

39:16.405 --> 39:17.965
Get some rest, Pravesh.

39:17.966 --> 39:19.566
Forget about your interns till tomorrow.

39:23.170 --> 39:24.412
- Mm.
- (GRAYSON WHOOPS)

39:24.413 --> 39:26.638
Yeah! 3B For Life, people. I mean,

39:26.639 --> 39:28.916
- we rocked America.
- BELL: Well, Andrea took the lead,

39:28.917 --> 39:30.116
- I just... I followed.
- Mm-hmm.

39:30.117 --> 39:32.202
- Yeah, what happened?
- No, it was great, really.

39:32.203 --> 39:34.514
We had a weight-loss
story and a heroic tale.

39:34.515 --> 39:35.964
Couldn't have planned it better.

39:35.965 --> 39:37.352
Which is hardly a surprise, I'd say.

39:37.353 --> 39:39.302
GRAYSON: Hey, what's going on?

39:39.303 --> 39:41.126
You know, Grayson
told me about your day,

39:41.127 --> 39:44.524
so I said I had to come by
and congratulate you in person.

39:44.525 --> 39:47.643
Dr. Barrett Cain. Chief of Surgery.

39:47.644 --> 39:49.574
- Um...
- Yes, I know. I know,

39:49.575 --> 39:51.586
this is a hard act to follow,
but I'm doing my best.

39:51.587 --> 39:53.291
Andrea Braydon.

39:53.292 --> 39:55.416
Would you, um, like s... Oh.

39:55.417 --> 39:57.098
Looks like we're running a little low.

39:57.099 --> 39:58.608
- Well, we'll have to get some more.
- ZIP: Oh, great.

39:58.609 --> 39:59.947
- Thank you very much.
- GRAYSON: That's-that's what I'm talking about.

39:59.948 --> 40:02.191
- (GRAYSON LAUGHS)
- Uh, Dr. Bell. Word, please?

40:07.164 --> 40:09.028
- ZIP: Well, cheers, guys.
- GRAYSON: Amazing.

40:09.029 --> 40:10.615
- Mazel tov.
- ZIP: Mazel tov.

40:10.616 --> 40:11.675
GRAYSON (CHUCKLES): Yeah.

40:13.220 --> 40:15.286
You know, it's only a matter of time

40:15.287 --> 40:17.959
before the board realizes
that you swiped an opportunity

40:17.960 --> 40:19.059
from underneath them.

40:19.060 --> 40:20.819
You rejected Andrea's pitch to them

40:20.820 --> 40:22.804
so you could have the
investment all to yourself.

40:22.805 --> 40:24.347
That's hardly what happened.

40:24.348 --> 40:25.973
And it's a high-risk investment,

40:25.974 --> 40:27.735
and one that Chastain would never make.

40:27.736 --> 40:29.402
Hmm.

40:29.403 --> 40:32.163
Well, that's not how I'm gonna spin it.

40:33.833 --> 40:35.207
(SIGHS)

40:36.527 --> 40:38.009
So what do you want?

40:38.010 --> 40:39.671
I don't know.

40:39.672 --> 40:43.157
A healthy percentage of our
growing supplement business.

40:43.158 --> 40:46.275
And in return I'll just smooth
things over with the board.

40:46.276 --> 40:48.059
Look, I have partners.

40:48.060 --> 40:49.330
- Right.
- It's hardly my decision to make.

40:49.331 --> 40:52.040
Yes, and I'm sure they will be thrilled

40:52.041 --> 40:54.161
to add another prestigious
physician with the product.

40:55.815 --> 40:58.765
And if anybody can
convince 'em, it's you.

40:58.766 --> 41:01.400
Ain't that right, partner?

41:07.349 --> 41:10.059
He's bringing it. Yeah. More bubbly.

41:10.060 --> 41:12.353
- (BABY CRYING)
- MINA: <i>♪ Three blind mice ♪</i>

41:12.354 --> 41:14.206
<i>♪ Three blind mice ♪</i>

41:14.207 --> 41:16.791
<i>♪ See how they run ♪</i>

41:19.045 --> 41:21.045
(CRYING CONTINUING)

41:30.056 --> 41:32.056
(CRYING STOPS)

41:52.936 --> 41:54.787
♪♪

42:12.932 --> 42:14.932
(PHONE VIBRATING)

42:19.232 --> 42:22.131
The answer is yes, I have
been dodging your calls.

42:22.132 --> 42:24.442
I am well aware.

42:24.443 --> 42:25.777
Guessing you heard I was fired.

42:25.778 --> 42:27.112
<i>You know, the truth is</i>

42:27.113 --> 42:28.920
I figured it would happen one day.

42:28.921 --> 42:30.179
You're a rule breaker.

42:33.602 --> 42:36.960
I've decided I'm not gonna
let them win so easily.

42:36.961 --> 42:38.790
Son, I've gone toe-to-toe

42:38.791 --> 42:41.367
with a lot of titans in my time.

42:41.368 --> 42:44.037
These Red Rock people...

42:44.038 --> 42:45.486
you're gonna have to bring

42:45.487 --> 42:47.799
more than a slingshot to this fight.

42:47.800 --> 42:49.634
<i>It's gonna get ugly.</i>

42:49.635 --> 42:51.427
<i>For all of us.</i>

42:52.805 --> 42:54.214
<i>I just want to make sure you know</i>

42:54.215 --> 42:56.141
<i>what we're up against.</i>

42:56.142 --> 42:58.960
I hear you, Dad. Thank you.

42:58.961 --> 43:00.628
- Hey.
- Hey.

43:00.629 --> 43:02.672
Missed you today.

43:02.673 --> 43:04.173
I missed you, too.

43:04.174 --> 43:05.675
It was a good day?

43:05.676 --> 43:08.344
Zero-g with Finn is just what I needed.

43:08.345 --> 43:10.905
- Oh, yeah?
- Mm.

43:11.827 --> 43:13.151
Red Rock came for me.

43:13.152 --> 43:14.651
Now I'm coming for them.

